President Joseph R. Biden Jr. has proclaimed October 2021 as National Clean Energy Action Month. The proclamation highlights the urgent need to address the climate crisis and the importance of transitioning to clean energy sources. The administration has set ambitious goals of achieving a 100 percent clean electricity sector by 2035 and reaching net-zero emissions economy-wide by 2050. The focus is on investing in and scaling up clean energy technologies such as solar and wind power, upgrading and expanding the power grid, and supporting the domestic supply chain for clean technologies. The administration also aims to create job opportunities in communities affected by the transition away from coal and fossil fuels. The proclamation emphasizes the role of individual actions in conserving energy and reducing emissions, as well as addressing environmental justice and ensuring that historically underserved communities benefit from clean energy. The goal is to create a safer, healthier, and more prosperous future for all Americans.